> I want this settled once and for all. A friend of mine who is really into animé says that Ghost in the Shell is all visuals and action; the psychology is meaningless and the plot basically simple. Is this true? And, bearing in mind that I liked Akira, loved Metropolis and am fairly addicted to Princess Mononoke, would I like GitS? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uotakulad.showPublicProfile?language=EN>OtakuLad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Canadian <img src=http://contest.polykarbon.com/badge1.gif></span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/31/02 10:41:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1928.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.calgarymedia.com/asuka.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Is GitS any good?</span><hr size=1> GitS is one of the best sci-fi pieces of work from the 90's. It examines humanity's relationship with machine from an almost spiritual level. Shirow's theme with GitS seemed to be &quot;Does the soul require a body?&quot;<br>
<br>
As for symbolism, I think it was great when Motoko is dodging machine gun fire from that tank and is climbing past that &quot;Evolutionary Tree&quot; on the wall. She flips right by Homo sapien...<br>
<br>
